Merlin story crosses the fluid cultural and linguistic boundaries between vernacular dialects on either side of the Alps, the protagonist accumulates histories, futures, and discourses from multiple texts within his omniscient knowledge. From his first appearance in Geoffrey of Monmouth's HistoriaRegum Britanniae, through thirteenth-century French romance, to fifteenth-century Venice, Merlin is the voice of political and spiritual truths that originate beyond the sphere of human comprehension. The study also shows howthe conversion of Merlin's prophetic speech from his omniscient mind into human languages parallels the work of the medieval translator. At the same time, the transmission of the Merlin story between vernacular French and Italiandialects presents an alternative model of translation, one that relies not on the displacement of previous texts, but instead on the accretion of information from text to text. Laura Chuhan Campbell is Assistant Professor of French at Durham University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aArthurian romancesxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturexHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aFrench literatureyTo 1500xHistory and criticism. 0aItalian literaturexHistory and criticismyTo 1500. 0aMerlin (Legendary character) in literature. 4aFrench Studies. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aarthurian.  acharacters.  aculture.  afantas.  afolklore.  afrench literature.  aitalian literature.  alanguage.  alinguistics.  amagic.  amedieval literature.  amedieval.  amerlin.  amiddle ages.  aprophecy.  areligion.  aromance.  aromantic literature.  asorcery.  aspirit.  awizard.  awizardry.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311143130740uhttps://